<li><a href="#org8ab0a21">71. Some of the possible questions that can be asked regarding Regulation M, along with the answers:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org91b11ca">71.1. Question: What is Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orga81842a">71.1.1. Answer: Regulation M is a set of rules enacted by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) to prevent manipulation of the market price of securities during a distribution. The rules prohibit certain activities, such as purchasing or bidding for securities, that could artificially inflate the price of the securities.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org35169ec">71.2. Question: What is the purpose of Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgdcc07d2">71.2.1. Answer: The purpose of Regulation M is to ensure that the market price of securities is not artificially inflated during a distribution. This is important because it protects investors from buying securities at inflated prices.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgf36c3a6">71.3. Question: Who is subject to Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgf1822f1">71.3.1. Answer: Regulation M applies to all companies that are distributing securities, including initial public offerings (IPOs), secondary offerings, and follow-on offerings. The rules also apply to any person who is participating in a distribution, such as an underwriter, broker-dealer, or selling security holder.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org0682da6">71.4. Question: What are the prohibited activities under Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org11d5a8d">71.4.1. Answer: The prohibited activities under Regulation M include:</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orge673289">71.5. Question: What are the exceptions to the prohibited activities under Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgb482767">71.5.1. Answer: There are a few exceptions to the prohibited activities under Regulation M. These exceptions include:</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgb1feba1">71.6. Question: How is Regulation M enforced?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgfd09093">71.6.1. Answer: Regulation M is enforced by the SEC. The SEC can bring civil enforcement actions against companies and individuals who violate Regulation M. The SEC can also impose civil penalties, such as fines and disgorgement of profits.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org98c64fd">71.7. Question: What are the penalties for violating Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgfd583a0">71.7.1. Answer: The penalties for violating Regulation M can be severe. The SEC can impose civil penalties, such as fines and disgorgement of profits. The SEC can also bring criminal charges against individuals who violate Regulation M.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgea31b2c">71.8. Question: What are the recent developments in Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgd7973ed">71.8.1. Answer: The SEC has recently updated Regulation M to clarify some of the rules and to make it easier for companies to comply. The SEC has also issued guidance on how Regulation M applies to certain types of transactions, such as exchange offers and tender offers.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org94b92d8">71.9. Question: What is the difference between Regulation M and Rule 10b-5?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org4af82b5">71.9.1. Answer: Regulation M and Rule 10b-5 are both rules that prohibit manipulative or deceptive trading practices. However, there are some key differences between the two rules. Regulation M specifically applies to distributions of securities, while Rule 10b-5 applies to all securities transactions. Additionally, Regulation M has a shorter restricted period than Rule 10b-5.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org38c8c8f">71.10. Question: What is the difference between Regulation M and Rule 10b-18?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org7fe4f7f">71.10.1. Answer: Regulation M and Rule 10b-18 are both rules that provide safe harbors from liability under Rule 10b-5 for certain repurchases of common stock. However, there are some key differences between the two rules. Regulation M applies to repurchases that are made during a distribution, while Rule 10b-18 applies to repurchases that are made outside of a distribution. Additionally, Regulation M has a more restrictive set of requirements than Rule 10b-18.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org2f754ac">71.11. Question: What are the implications of Regulation M for issuers?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org29428e1">71.11.1. Answer: Regulation M has a number of implications for issuers. First, issuers must comply with the rules of Regulation M when they distribute securities. Second, issuers must be aware of the exceptions to the rules of Regulation M. Third, issuers must be aware of the penalties for violating Regulation M.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org534cd70">71.12. Question: What are the implications of Regulation M for investors?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org00f46f6">71.12.1. Answer: Regulation M has a number of implications for investors. First, investors can be confident that the market price of securities is not being artificially inflated during a distribution. Second, investors can be aware of the exceptions to the rules of Regulation M. Third, investors can be aware of the penalties for violating Regulation M.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org9a3e55a">71.13. Question: What are the best practices for compliance with Regulation M?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgb002132">71.13.1. Answer: There are a number of best practices for compliance with Regulation M. These best practices include:</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org1ef22ec">72. Some of the key restrictions on stabilizing activities under Regulation M:</a></li>
<li><a href="#orga10e537">73. Possible questions that can be asked in Series 57 regarding stabilizing and Regulation M:</a></li>
<li><a href="#org2726c4b">74. Sequence of all stages of an IPO, including the date of pricing, start of restricted period, start of distribution period, and IPO:</a></li>
<li><a href="#org3b82c4d">75. Possible questions regarding 10b5-1 plans:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org645014d">75.1. Question: What is a 10b5-1 plan?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org350a1a6">75.1.1. Answer: A 10b5-1 plan is a written plan that allows a person to pre-determine the purchase or sale of securities of a company. This can be useful for insiders who want to avoid the appearance of insider trading.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgfffa336">75.2. Question: What are the requirements for a valid 10b5-1 plan?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orge8390d8">75.2.1. Answer: The plan must be in writing and it must be adopted before the person has any material non-public information about the company. The plan must also specify the amount of securities that can be purchased or sold, the price at which they can be purchased or sold, and the date on which the purchase or sale can occur.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org9e44295">75.3. Question: What are the benefits of having a 10b5-1 plan?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org7837949">75.3.1. Answer: 10b5-1 plans can help insiders avoid the appearance of insider trading. They can also help insiders to manage their investment portfolios more effectively.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org0b165f3">75.4. Question: What are the risks of having a 10b5-1 plan?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org6964c8f">75.4.1. Answer: If a 10b5-1 plan is not properly drafted or implemented, it could be challenged in court. Additionally, if the person who has adopted a 10b5-1 plan trades in the securities of the company in a way that is inconsistent with the plan, they could be liable for insider trading.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org1c06a9b">75.5. Question: What are the penalties for violating the rules governing 10b5-1 plans?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orga7e4735">75.5.1. Answer: The penalties for violating the rules governing 10b5-1 plans can be severe. The SEC can impose civil penalties, such as fines and disgorgement of profits. The SEC can also bring criminal charges against individuals who violate the rules.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org90c1cdc">76. Possible questions regarding Rule 10b-5, followed by the answer:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orga04d9f4">76.1. Question: What is Rule 10b-5?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgd56f3c5">76.1.1. Answer: Rule 10b-5 is a rule of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that prohibits the use of manipulative and deceptive devices in the trading of securities. It is one of the most important anti-fraud provisions in the securities laws.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org4101ee1">76.2. Question: What is material non-public information?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgab1bb63">76.2.1. Answer: Material non-public information is information that could significantly affect the price of a security if it were known to the public. This could include information about the company's financial performance, mergers and acquisitions, or product development.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org456787a">76.3. Question: What is insider trading?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgf434743">76.3.1. Answer: Insider trading is the buying or selling of a security based on material non-public information. It is a form of securities fraud that can have serious consequences for the individuals involved.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org2bb7725">76.4. Question: What are the penalties for insider trading?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org60bc2b0">76.4.1. Answer: The penalties for insider trading can be severe. Individuals who are convicted of insider trading can be fined up to $5 million and/or imprisoned for up to 20 years.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org1c390a1">76.5. Question: How can I avoid insider trading?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org930e2ac">76.5.1. Answer: There are a number of things you can do to avoid insider trading. First, you should be aware of the rules governing insider trading. Second, you should avoid trading in securities if you have any material non-public information about the company. Third, you should be careful about what you say to others about material non-public information.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org6ce66bf">77. Possible questions regarding stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering, followed by the answer:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgb7e4aa1">77.1. Question: What is stabilizing?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgfbc332b">77.1.1. Answer: Stabilizing is a practice by underwriters to buy back shares of a newly-issued security in order to keep the price from falling below the offering price. This is done to prevent investors from selling their shares at a loss and to create a more stable market for the security.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgd68aad5">77.2. Question: When is stabilizing allowed?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgf11824e">77.2.1. Answer: Stabilizing is only allowed during a limited period of time after the IPO or secondary offering. The exact period of time varies depending on the jurisdiction, but it is typically five business days.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orga1feda2">77.3. Question: How does stabilizing work?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgdb43a28">77.3.1. Answer: Underwriters will typically set a stabilizing bid, which is the price at which they are willing to buy back shares. If the price of the security falls below the stabilizing bid, the underwriters will buy back shares in order to prop up the price.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org39d6ccb">77.4. Question: What are the risks of stabilizing?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org1aaa012">77.4.1. Answer: Stabilizing can be risky for underwriters. If the price of the security falls too far, the underwriters could lose money on the stabilizing bid. Additionally, stabilizing can be seen as manipulative by regulators, and underwriters could face sanctions if they are not careful.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgc2e1677">77.5. Question: Is stabilizing legal?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org9af1658">77.5.1. Answer: Stabilizing is legal in most jurisdictions, but there are some restrictions. For example, underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org468a977">78. Additional questions and answers about stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org2b65ba7">78.1. Question: Can stabilizing be done on ask prices?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org78f1295">78.1.1. Answer: No, stabilizing can only be done on bid prices. This is because stabilizing is intended to prop up the price of the security, and if the underwriters were to buy on the ask, they would be buying at a higher price than the current market price.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org8419a3a">78.2. Question: What are the rules for stabilizing bids?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org6ebf0fc">78.2.1. Answer: The rules for stabilizing bids vary depending on the jurisdiction, but there are some general principles that apply. First, the stabilizing bid must be made at a price that is no higher than the initial offering price. Second, the stabilizing bid must be made in a way that does not manipulate the market. Third, the underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org8f65b3b">78.3. Question: What is the relationship between the closing price, the initial offering price, and the last traded price?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orga85d126">78.3.1. Answer: The closing price is the price at which the security closed on the first day of trading. The initial offering price is the price at which the security was offered to the public. The last traded price is the price at which the security was last traded on the day of the IPO.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgd46252b">78.4. Question: What happens if the closing price is below the initial offering price?</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgb55190a">79. Possible examination questions related to stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering, followed by the answer:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org5e423b0">79.1. Question: Underwriters are allowed to stabilize the price of a security after an IPO or secondary offering. What are the rules governing stabilizing bids?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org59936eb">79.1.1. Answer: The rules for stabilizing bids vary depending on the jurisdiction, but there are some general principles that apply. First, the stabilizing bid must be made at a price that is no higher than the initial offering price. Second, the stabilizing bid must be made in a way that does not manipulate the market. Third, the underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org82b47cf">79.2. Question: What happens if the closing price is below the initial offering price?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org3d71c12">79.2.1. Answer: If the closing price is below the initial offering price, the underwriters may continue to stabilize the price of the security. However, they may also choose to abandon the stabilizing effort. If the underwriters abandon the stabilizing effort, the price of the security could fall further.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgb0c1cc7">79.3. Question: What is the difference between stabilizing and market manipulation?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org4612ffe">79.3.1. Answer: Stabilizing is a legitimate practice that is allowed by regulators. Market manipulation is a fraudulent practice that is not allowed by regulators. The key difference between the two is that stabilizing is intended to prop up the price of a security, while market manipulation is intended to artificially inflate the price of a security.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orge0649ad">79.4. Question: What are the risks of stabilizing?</a>
