<div id="outline-container-org8ab0a21" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org8ab0a21"><span class="section-number-2">71.</span> Some of the possible questions that can be asked regarding Regulation M, along with the answers:</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-71">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org91b11ca" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org91b11ca"><span class="section-number-3">71.1.</span> Question: What is Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orga81842a" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orga81842a"><span class="section-number-4">71.1.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M is a set of rules enacted by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) to prevent manipulation of the market price of securities during a distribution. The rules prohibit certain activities, such as purchasing or bidding for securities, that could artificially inflate the price of the securities.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org35169ec" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org35169ec"><span class="section-number-3">71.2.</span> Question: What is the purpose of Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgdcc07d2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgdcc07d2"><span class="section-number-4">71.2.1.</span> Answer: The purpose of Regulation M is to ensure that the market price of securities is not artificially inflated during a distribution. This is important because it protects investors from buying securities at inflated prices.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgf36c3a6" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf36c3a6"><span class="section-number-3">71.3.</span> Question: Who is subject to Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-3">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgf1822f1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgf1822f1"><span class="section-number-4">71.3.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M applies to all companies that are distributing securities, including initial public offerings (IPOs), secondary offerings, and follow-on offerings. The rules also apply to any person who is participating in a distribution, such as an underwriter, broker-dealer, or selling security holder.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org0682da6" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org0682da6"><span class="section-number-3">71.4.</span> Question: What are the prohibited activities under Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-4">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org11d5a8d" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org11d5a8d"><span class="section-number-4">71.4.1.</span> Answer: The prohibited activities under Regulation M include:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-71-4-1">
<p>
Purchasing or bidding for securities during the restricted period.
Entering into a stabilizing agreement.
Engaging in a short sale during the restricted period.
Causing any of the prohibited activities to occur.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orge673289" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orge673289"><span class="section-number-3">71.5.</span> Question: What are the exceptions to the prohibited activities under Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-5">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgb482767" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgb482767"><span class="section-number-4">71.5.1.</span> Answer: There are a few exceptions to the prohibited activities under Regulation M. These exceptions include:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-71-5-1">
<p>
Purchases made in the ordinary course of business.
Purchases made by bona fide market makers.
Purchases made by institutional investors.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgb1feba1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgb1feba1"><span class="section-number-3">71.6.</span> Question: How is Regulation M enforced?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-6">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgfd09093" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgfd09093"><span class="section-number-4">71.6.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M is enforced by the SEC. The SEC can bring civil enforcement actions against companies and individuals who violate Regulation M. The SEC can also impose civil penalties, such as fines and disgorgement of profits.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org98c64fd" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org98c64fd"><span class="section-number-3">71.7.</span> Question: What are the penalties for violating Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-7">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgfd583a0" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgfd583a0"><span class="section-number-4">71.7.1.</span> Answer: The penalties for violating Regulation M can be severe. The SEC can impose civil penalties, such as fines and disgorgement of profits. The SEC can also bring criminal charges against individuals who violate Regulation M.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgea31b2c" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgea31b2c"><span class="section-number-3">71.8.</span> Question: What are the recent developments in Regulation M?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-8">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgd7973ed" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgd7973ed"><span class="section-number-4">71.8.1.</span> Answer: The SEC has recently updated Regulation M to clarify some of the rules and to make it easier for companies to comply. The SEC has also issued guidance on how Regulation M applies to certain types of transactions, such as exchange offers and tender offers.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org94b92d8" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org94b92d8"><span class="section-number-3">71.9.</span> Question: What is the difference between Regulation M and Rule 10b-5?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-9">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org4af82b5" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org4af82b5"><span class="section-number-4">71.9.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M and Rule 10b-5 are both rules that prohibit manipulative or deceptive trading practices. However, there are some key differences between the two rules. Regulation M specifically applies to distributions of securities, while Rule 10b-5 applies to all securities transactions. Additionally, Regulation M has a shorter restricted period than Rule 10b-5.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org38c8c8f" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org38c8c8f"><span class="section-number-3">71.10.</span> Question: What is the difference between Regulation M and Rule 10b-18?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-10">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org7fe4f7f" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org7fe4f7f"><span class="section-number-4">71.10.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M and Rule 10b-18 are both rules that provide safe harbors from liability under Rule 10b-5 for certain repurchases of common stock. However, there are some key differences between the two rules. Regulation M applies to repurchases that are made during a distribution, while Rule 10b-18 applies to repurchases that are made outside of a distribution. Additionally, Regulation M has a more restrictive set of requirements than Rule 10b-18.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org2f754ac" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2f754ac"><span class="section-number-3">71.11.</span> Question: What are the implications of Regulation M for issuers?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-71-11">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org29428e1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org29428e1"><span class="section-number-4">71.11.1.</span> Answer: Regulation M has a number of implications for issuers. First, issuers must comply with the rules of Regulation M when they distribute securities. Second, issuers must be aware of the exceptions to the rules of Regulation M. Third, issuers must be aware of the penalties for violating Regulation M.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org534cd70" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org534cd70"><span class="section-number-3">71.12.</span> Question: What are the implications of Regulation M for investors?</h3>
