<div id="outline-container-org6ce66bf" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org6ce66bf"><span class="section-number-2">77.</span> Possible questions regarding stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering, followed by the answer:</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-77">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgb7e4aa1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgb7e4aa1"><span class="section-number-3">77.1.</span> Question: What is stabilizing?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-77-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgfbc332b" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgfbc332b"><span class="section-number-4">77.1.1.</span> Answer: Stabilizing is a practice by underwriters to buy back shares of a newly-issued security in order to keep the price from falling below the offering price. This is done to prevent investors from selling their shares at a loss and to create a more stable market for the security.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgd68aad5" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgd68aad5"><span class="section-number-3">77.2.</span> Question: When is stabilizing allowed?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-77-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgf11824e" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgf11824e"><span class="section-number-4">77.2.1.</span> Answer: Stabilizing is only allowed during a limited period of time after the IPO or secondary offering. The exact period of time varies depending on the jurisdiction, but it is typically five business days.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orga1feda2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orga1feda2"><span class="section-number-3">77.3.</span> Question: How does stabilizing work?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-77-3">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgdb43a28" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgdb43a28"><span class="section-number-4">77.3.1.</span> Answer: Underwriters will typically set a stabilizing bid, which is the price at which they are willing to buy back shares. If the price of the security falls below the stabilizing bid, the underwriters will buy back shares in order to prop up the price.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org39d6ccb" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org39d6ccb"><span class="section-number-3">77.4.</span> Question: What are the risks of stabilizing?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-77-4">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org1aaa012" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org1aaa012"><span class="section-number-4">77.4.1.</span> Answer: Stabilizing can be risky for underwriters. If the price of the security falls too far, the underwriters could lose money on the stabilizing bid. Additionally, stabilizing can be seen as manipulative by regulators, and underwriters could face sanctions if they are not careful.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgc2e1677" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgc2e1677"><span class="section-number-3">77.5.</span> Question: Is stabilizing legal?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-77-5">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org9af1658" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org9af1658"><span class="section-number-4">77.5.1.</span> Answer: Stabilizing is legal in most jurisdictions, but there are some restrictions. For example, underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-77-5-1">
<p>
I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.
</p>

