<div id="outline-container-org468a977" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org468a977"><span class="section-number-2">78.</span> Additional questions and answers about stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering:</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-78">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org2b65ba7" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2b65ba7"><span class="section-number-3">78.1.</span> Question: Can stabilizing be done on ask prices?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-78-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org78f1295" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org78f1295"><span class="section-number-4">78.1.1.</span> Answer: No, stabilizing can only be done on bid prices. This is because stabilizing is intended to prop up the price of the security, and if the underwriters were to buy on the ask, they would be buying at a higher price than the current market price.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org8419a3a" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8419a3a"><span class="section-number-3">78.2.</span> Question: What are the rules for stabilizing bids?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-78-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org6ebf0fc" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org6ebf0fc"><span class="section-number-4">78.2.1.</span> Answer: The rules for stabilizing bids vary depending on the jurisdiction, but there are some general principles that apply. First, the stabilizing bid must be made at a price that is no higher than the initial offering price. Second, the stabilizing bid must be made in a way that does not manipulate the market. Third, the underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org8f65b3b" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8f65b3b"><span class="section-number-3">78.3.</span> Question: What is the relationship between the closing price, the initial offering price, and the last traded price?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-78-3">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orga85d126" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orga85d126"><span class="section-number-4">78.3.1.</span> Answer: The closing price is the price at which the security closed on the first day of trading. The initial offering price is the price at which the security was offered to the public. The last traded price is the price at which the security was last traded on the day of the IPO.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgd46252b" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgd46252b"><span class="section-number-3">78.4.</span> Question: What happens if the closing price is below the initial offering price?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-78-4">
<p>
If the closing price is below the initial offering price, the underwriters may continue to stabilize the price of the security. However, they may also choose to abandon the stabilizing effort. If the underwriters abandon the stabilizing effort, the price of the security could fall further.
</p>

<p>
I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.
</p>

