<div id="outline-container-orgb55190a" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgb55190a"><span class="section-number-2">79.</span> Possible examination questions related to stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering, followed by the answer:</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-79">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org5e423b0" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org5e423b0"><span class="section-number-3">79.1.</span> Question: Underwriters are allowed to stabilize the price of a security after an IPO or secondary offering. What are the rules governing stabilizing bids?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org59936eb" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org59936eb"><span class="section-number-4">79.1.1.</span> Answer: The rules for stabilizing bids vary depending on the jurisdiction, but there are some general principles that apply. First, the stabilizing bid must be made at a price that is no higher than the initial offering price. Second, the stabilizing bid must be made in a way that does not manipulate the market. Third, the underwriters must disclose their stabilizing activities to the public.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org82b47cf" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org82b47cf"><span class="section-number-3">79.2.</span> Question: What happens if the closing price is below the initial offering price?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org3d71c12" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org3d71c12"><span class="section-number-4">79.2.1.</span> Answer: If the closing price is below the initial offering price, the underwriters may continue to stabilize the price of the security. However, they may also choose to abandon the stabilizing effort. If the underwriters abandon the stabilizing effort, the price of the security could fall further.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgb0c1cc7" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgb0c1cc7"><span class="section-number-3">79.3.</span> Question: What is the difference between stabilizing and market manipulation?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-3">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org4612ffe" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org4612ffe"><span class="section-number-4">79.3.1.</span> Answer: Stabilizing is a legitimate practice that is allowed by regulators. Market manipulation is a fraudulent practice that is not allowed by regulators. The key difference between the two is that stabilizing is intended to prop up the price of a security, while market manipulation is intended to artificially inflate the price of a security.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orge0649ad" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orge0649ad"><span class="section-number-3">79.4.</span> Question: What are the risks of stabilizing?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-4">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org6c93fd3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org6c93fd3"><span class="section-number-4">79.4.1.</span> Answer: The risks of stabilizing include:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-79-4-1">
<p>
The underwriter could lose money if the price of the security falls too far.
The underwriter could be accused of market manipulation.
The underwriter could face regulatory sanctions.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org720e263" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org720e263"><span class="section-number-3">79.5.</span> Question: What are the benefits of stabilizing?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-5">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orge17a108" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orge17a108"><span class="section-number-4">79.5.1.</span> Answer: The benefits of stabilizing include:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-79-5-1">
<p>
It can help to prevent investors from selling their shares at a loss.
It can create a more stable market for the security.
It can enhance the reputation of the underwriter.
I hope these questions help you to understand the fundamentals of stabilizing after an IPO or secondary offering.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgacdc39c" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgacdc39c"><span class="section-number-3">79.6.</span> Question: What is Rule 10b-18?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-6">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org13c831c" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org13c831c"><span class="section-number-4">79.6.1.</span> Answer: Rule 10b-18 is a Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) rule that provides a safe harbor for repurchases of a company's own stock. The rule allows companies to repurchase their stock without being accused of market manipulation, as long as they follow certain procedures.</h4>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org8f53aab" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8f53aab"><span class="section-number-3">79.7.</span> Question: What are the requirements of Rule 10b-18?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-7">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org42c5ca8" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org42c5ca8"><span class="section-number-4">79.7.1.</span> Answer: The requirements of Rule 10b-18 are:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-79-7-1">
<p>
The repurchases must be made in accordance with a plan that has been filed with the SEC.
The repurchases must be made at a price that is no higher than the average price of the stock over the preceding 40 trading days.
The repurchases must not be made in an amount that exceeds 25% of the company's outstanding stock.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orge403329" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orge403329"><span class="section-number-3">79.8.</span> Question: What are the exceptions to Rule 10b-18?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-8">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orga8ff106" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orga8ff106"><span class="section-number-4">79.8.1.</span> Answer: There are a few exceptions to Rule 10b-18. These exceptions include:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-79-8-1">
<p>
Repurchases that are made to satisfy employee stock options or warrants.
Repurchases that are made to meet a sinking fund requirement.
Repurchases that are made to repurchase shares that were issued in a merger or acquisition.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org2a270d3" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2a270d3"><span class="section-number-3">79.9.</span> Question: What are the penalties for violating Rule 10b-18?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-79-9">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgd8e5274" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgd8e5274"><span class="section-number-4">79.9.1.</span> Answer: The penalties for violating Rule 10b-18 can be severe. Companies that violate the rule can be fined up to \$10 million, and individuals can be fined up to \$5 million and imprisoned for up to 20 years.</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-79-9-1">
<p>
What is the difference between a block repurchase and a non-block repurchase?
What is the purpose of the 40-trading-day average price requirement?
What are the procedures for filing a repurchase plan with the SEC?
What are the steps that a company must take if it wants to repurchase its stock in excess of the 25% limit?
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org34aa4b0" class="outline-3">
